b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n<workbook_page id="p1_amount_substance" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title>Chemical Reactions: Moles and Particles</title>\n        <objref idref="stoich"/>\n\n    </head>\n\n    <body>\n        <p><activity_link idref="Periodic_Table" target="new"><em>Reference: The Periodic Table of\n                    Elements</em></activity_link></p>\n        <section id="p1_amount_substance_DE1">\n          <title></title>\n          <body>  <p>A balanced chemical equation provides a great deal of information in a very succinct\n            format. Chemical formulas provide the identities of the reactants and products involved\n            in the chemical change, allowing classification of the reaction. Coefficients provide\n            the relative numbers of these chemical species, allowing a quantitative assessment of\n            the relationships between the amounts of substances consumed and produced by the\n            reaction. These quantitative relationships are known as the reaction\xe2\x80\x99s <extra>\n                <anchor>stoichiometry</anchor>\n                <meaning>\n                    <material>\n                        <p>relationships between the amounts of reactants and products of a chemical\n                            reaction</p>\n                    </material>\n                </meaning>\n            </extra>, a term derived from the Greek words stoicheion (meaning \xe2\x80\x9celement\xe2\x80\x9d) and metron\n            (meaning \xe2\x80\x9cmeasure\xe2\x80\x9d). In this module, the use of balanced chemical equations for various\n            stoichiometric applications is explored.</p>\n\n        <p>The general approach to using stoichiometric relationships is similar in concept to the\n            way people go about many common activities. Food preparation, for example, offers an\n            appropriate comparison. A recipe for making eight pancakes calls for 1 cup pancake mix,\n            3/4 cup milk, and one egg. The \xe2\x80\x9cequation\xe2\x80\x9d representing the preparation of pancakes per\n            this recipe is</p>\n        <formula>$$1\\;\\mathrm{cup}\\;\\mathrm{mix}\\;+\\;\\frac34\\;\\mathrm{cup}\\;\\mathrm{milk}\\;+\\;1\\;\\mathrm{egg}\\;=\\;8\\;\\mathrm{pancakes}$$</formula>\n\n\n        <p>If two dozen pancakes are needed for a big family breakfast, the ingredient amounts must\n            be increased proportionally according to the amounts given in the recipe. For example,\n            the number of eggs required to make 24 pancakes is</p>\n        <formula>$$\\require{cancel}24\\cancel{\\;\\mathrm{pancakes}}\\;\\times\\frac{1\\;\\mathrm{egg}}{8\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{pancakes}}}\\;=\\;3\\;\\mathrm{eggs}$$</formula>\n\n\n        <p>Balanced chemical equations are used in much the same fashion to determine the amount of\n            one reactant required to react with a given amount of another reactant, or to yield a\n            given amount of product, and so forth. The coefficients in the balanced equation are\n            used to derive <extra>\n                <anchor>stoichiometric factors</anchor>\n                <meaning>\n                    <material>\n                        <p>ratio of coefficients in a balanced chemical equation, used in\n                            computations relating amounts of reactants and products</p>\n                    </material>\n                </meaning>\n            </extra> that permit computation of the desired quantity. To illustrate this idea,\n            consider the production of ammonia by reaction of hydrogen and nitrogen:</p>\n        <formula>$${\\mathrm N}_2(g)\\;+\\;3\\;{\\mathrm\n            H}_2(g)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;2\\;{\\mathrm{NH}}_3(g)$$</formula>\n\n\n        <p>This equation shows ammonia molecules are produced from hydrogen molecules in a 2:3\n            ratio, and stoichiometric factors may be derived using any amount (number) unit:</p>\n        <formula>$$\\frac{2\\;{\\mathrm{NH}}_3\\;\\mathrm{molecules}}{3\\;{\\mathrm\n            H}_2\\;\\mathrm{molecules}}\\;\\mathrm{or}\\;\\frac{2\\;\\mathrm{doz}\\;{\\mathrm{NH}}_3\\;\\mathrm{molecules}}{3\\;\\mathrm{doz}\\;{\\mathrm\n            H}_2\\;\\mathrm{molecules}}\\;\\;\\mathrm{or}\\;\\frac{2\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm{NH}}_3\\;\\mathrm{molecules}}{3\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm\n            H}_2\\;\\mathrm{molecules}}$$</formula>\n\n        <p>These stoichiometric factors can be used to compute the number of ammonia molecules\n            produced from a given number of hydrogen molecules, or the number of hydrogen molecules\n            required to produce a given number of ammonia molecules. Similar factors may be derived\n            for any pair of substances in any chemical equation.</p></body></section>\n\n        <example id="p1_amount_substance_EX1">\n\n            <p>How many moles of I<sub>2</sub> are required to react with 0.429 mol of Al according\n                to the following equation?</p>\n            <formula>$$2\\;\\mathrm{Al}\\;+\\;3\\;{\\mathrm\n                I}_2\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;2\\;{\\mathrm{AlI}}_3$$</formula>\n\n\n            <p>Referring to the balanced chemical equation, the stoichiometric factor relating the\n                two substances of interest is 3 mol I<sub>2</sub> mol/ 2 mol Al. The molar amount of\n                iodine is derived by multiplying the provided molar amount of aluminum by this\n                factor:</p>\n\n            <image src="../webcontent/stoic.png"\n                alt="This figure shows two pink rectangles. The first is labeled, \xe2\x80\x9cMoles of A l.\xe2\x80\x9d This rectangle is followed by an arrow pointing right to a second rectangle labeled, \xe2\x80\x9cMoles of I subscript 2.\xe2\x80\x9d"/>\n\n            <formula>$$\\require{cancel}\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm\n                I}_2\\;=\\;0.429\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{Al}}\\;\\times\\frac{3\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm\n                I}_2}{2\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{Al}}}\\;=\\;0.644\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm\n                I}_2\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\\\\\end{array}$$</formula>\n\n\n        </example>\n        <wb:inline idref="mol_part_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n        <p>We can also use the stoichiometric relationships in a balanced equation to determine the\n            number of particles (atoms, molecules, or formula units) involved in a chemical\n            reaction. </p>\n\n        <example id="p1_amount_substance_EX2">\n\n            <p>How many carbon dioxide molecules are produced when 0.75 mol of propane is combusted\n                according to this equation? </p>\n            <formula>$${\\mathrm C}_3{\\mathrm H}_8\\;+\\;5\\;{\\mathrm\n                O}_2\\;\\longrightarrow\\;3\\;{\\mathrm{CO}}_2\\;+\\;4\\;{\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm O$$</formula>\n\n\n            <p>The approach here is the same as in the previous example, though the absolute number\n                of molecules is requested, not the number of moles of molecules. This will simply\n                require use of the moles-to-numbers conversion factor, Avogadro\xe2\x80\x99s number.</p>\n\n            <p>The balanced equation shows that carbon dioxide is produced from propane in a 3:1\n                ratio:</p>\n\n            <image src="../webcontent/mole_convert.png" width="400"\n                alt="To convert from moles of C3H8 to moles of CO2 use the stoichiometric factor. To convert from moles of CO2 to molecules of CO2 use Avogadro\'s number."/>\n\n            <formula>$$\\require{cancel}0.75\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm C}_3{\\mathrm\n                H}_8}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{3\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm{CO}}_2}}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm\n                C}_3{\\mathrm\n                H}_8}}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{6.02\\times10^{23}\\;\\mathrm{molecules}\\;{\\mathrm{CO}}_2}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm{CO}}_2}}\\;=\\;1.4\\times10^{24}\\;\\mathrm{molecules}\\;{\\mathrm{CO}}_2$$</formula>\n        </example>\n        <wb:inline idref="mol_part_lbd2" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n        <wb:inline idref="mol_part_digt" purpose="didigetthis"/>\n        \n        <p>Adapted from <link href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\n                >Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\n                href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"> Creative Commons Attribution\n                4.0 License. </link></p>\n        <p>Download for free at <link\n                href="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\n                >http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link></p>\n\n\n\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'